at options beyond the domestic economy and the socialist bloc. In the 1970s, Central and Eastern European socialist leaders intensified engagements with the capitalist West in order to expand access to markets, technology, and capital. This shift began to challenge the Stalinist developmental model in favor of exports and transnational integration. A new reliance on exports launched the integration of Eastern European industry into value chains that cut across the East-West political divide. After 1989, these chains proved to be critical gateways to foreign direct investment and circuits of global capitalism. This book enriches our understanding of a regional shift that began well before the fall of the wall, while also explaining the distinct international roles that Central and Eastern European states have assumed in the globalized twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspectszEurope, EasternxHistory. 0aGlobalization. 4aEconomic Reform. 4aForeign Direct Investment. 4aGlobalization. 4aPolitical Economy. 4aPostcommunism. 4aPostsocialism. 4aTransition Economies. 4aTransnational Production. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503605985zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605985423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605985.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles